  text: |-
    Jeong Do-jeon rose from humble origins, stealing his way into the office of Dang-sa, seeking to obscure his lowborn roots. Wishing to be rid of his former master, he lacked the means to act alone. So he wove false accusations, ensnaring many innocent souls in their net. Zhao Jun, having grown enemies with one or two ministers by chance, joined hearts with Do-jeon in this treachery. Together they fanned the flames of rebellion, peddling power and coercing all around them. Those who feared losing their positions, those who craved favor—all rose like echoes responding to a call. Among them, Nam Eun and Nam Jae became the wings of sedition. Yun So-jong and Zhao Po became the mouth speaking lies. They sang in chorus, casting wide their nets of accusation, inflicting punishment on the innocent, seeking guilt where none existed. The people trembled with dread and murmured in despair. This first wounded the harmony of Heaven and Earth's creation. Second, it damaged Your Majesty's virtuous love of life.

    In the year kyŏngngо, great floods ravaged Cheongju. In the year sinmi, the very streets became rivers. These calamities followed in succession. The harvests failed. Are these not the consequences they summoned?

    Your Majesty might say Zhao Jun should be pardoned as a merit-maker, despite his crimes. Yet we have heard that in the year mugjin, the Founder's intention to establish Your Majesty had already taken root on the day the armies turned back—yet Zhao Jun was not among them, clearly having no part in these deliberations. By the year gisa, the Founder's resolve was already fixed. Zhao Jun opposed it, speaking of other matters. Only because the Founder refused him did Your Majesty ascend. By this reckoning, Zhao Jun participated not in the early planning, nor later in its execution, but rather opposed what was already determined. Can such a man be called Your Majesty's merit-maker?

    Should Zhao Jun claim he never spoke thus, know that not only the ministers heard him—Heaven itself listens to what is spoken below. It is bright and terrible. How can it be concealed?

    Ah, how profound is the loyalty of the Founder! He thwarted the false dynasty's schemes to disturb the great civilizations, thus saving these people. He rejected Zhao Jun's plot to establish another, thus establishing Your Majesty. Such loyalty pierces through sun and moon themselves. Had the armies marched a thousand li, challenging the celestial court, could this people have worn their clothes and eaten their fill in peace? How much less when the Son of Heaven himself sent envoys bearing treasures from the imperial treasury, favoring the crown prince and raising him above all other princes?

    Zhao Jun's words reveal his heart. Thus he is no merit-maker, but truly a disloyal minister. Yet by fortune's favor, he gained the name of merit-maker, ranks among them, has his likeness painted for posterity, stands equal to the greatest. He receives ranks beyond his station, gains ten times the honors of true merit-makers, yet knows no limit to his glory. Still he shows no thought of correcting himself or hiding his shame. Rather, he secretly gathers with those wings and mouths of sedition, scheming endlessly. Is this happenstance? We fear that if his plots do not succeed, yet deeper disloyalty may emerge. Would it not be better to act now, before this spreads further?

    Moreover, we hear that Zhao Jun weeps and wails before Your Majesty, feigning reform while secretly plotting leniency. This is false repentance. Your Majesty, being naturally just, takes it as sincere. We greatly lament this. If Zhao Jun had truly awakened to yesterday's errors when Heaven touched his heart at the height of his villainy, his repentance would be genuine. But now his fellow conspirators, the wing and the mouth of sedition, have folded their wings. The people's rage and suspicion have reached their peak. How could he escape punishment? This is necessity, not choice. What is this but false repentance? Should he gain power again, the chaos will surely exceed what came before. We humbly pray that Your Majesty should not trust him, but act swiftly.

    Furthermore, we hear that Nam Eun once said, "Your Majesty conceals many desires beneath outward benevolence and righteousness." What does this mean? Nam Eun has no exceptional merit for the state, yet suddenly rose to high office—Your Majesty's grace was immense. Yet he seeks only to please Zhao Jun and Do-jeon, showing no gratitude, no satisfaction. He dares speak words both disrespectful and insulting, seeking to move Your Majesty's heart to further his ambitions. His intentions are so villainous as to inspire dread.

    These men's sins are equal. Should Your Majesty hesitate and fail to act decisively, not only will Heaven's wrath and the people's resentment follow, but a remorse too late to remedy may ensue.

    We are not men who wish harm upon others, nor do we imitate those who harbor private grudges. But public righteousness demands it. The circumstances compel it. We dare not remain silent. If these words contain any falsehood, may Heaven itself punish us first. How can we not tremble at this?

    We humbly pray that Your Majesty strip Zhao Jun, Nam Eun, Nam Jae, Yun So-jong, and Zhao Po of their offices and merit certificates, investigate their crimes thoroughly, and apply the law with clarity. As for Jeong Do-jeon, let him be punished in his place of exile, that a warning may reach those who come after.
  footnotes:
    - The Founder (開國伯) refers to Yi Seong-gye, who established the Joseon Dynasty.
    - This memorial, submitted by Kim Jin-yang at the instigation of Jeong Mong-ju, seeks to eliminate the Founder's supporters first, before moving against the Founder himself.
    - The years mentioned (kyŏngngо and sinmi) refer to natural disasters interpreted as heavenly signs of displeasure with the coup.
    - Nam Eun's alleged statement about the King concealing desires beneath virtue is presented as evidence of his disloyalty and manipulative nature.
